{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b68582fd-1082-410f-b572-6d1e660e4d57","content":"> **Note:** `${backend}` appears to be an unresolved placeholder — I analyzed the project directly.\n\nHere are the MSBuild evaluation performance issues found:\n\n### 1. Broad recursive wildcard glob (line 9, `.csproj`)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n`**\\*.*` forces MSBuild to walk the **entire directory tree** during evaluation. This is one of the most expensive evaluation patterns — cost grows with every file added to the repo.\n\n### 2. File I/O via property function (line 13, `.csproj`)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes … >$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nSynchronous file reads during evaluation block the evaluator. The `build-notes.txt` file itself warns about this. Property functions that do I/O should be avoided or deferred to a target.\n\n### 3. Three-level chained import chain\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nEach `<Import>` adds evaluation overhead. The chain is linear and could be flattened. While 3 levels is modest, it's a pattern that compounds as the project grows.\n\n**Recommended fixes:**\n- **Glob:** Narrow the `Include` to specific extensions (e.g., `**\\*.txt`) or a specific subdirectory.\n- **File read:** Move `ReadAllText` into a `<Target>` so it runs at build time, not evaluation time.\n- **Imports:** Flatten the chain or merge the simple property groups into fewer files.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b64ced06-2a56-4901-924c-58ed0f806839","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have a complete picture of the project. Let me analyze the MSBuild evaluation performance issues.\n\nNote about `${backend}`: This looks like a template variable that wasn't resolved. I'll just note this and proceed with the analysis.\n\nHere are the performance issues I can identify:\n\n1. **Recursive wildcard glob** (`**\\*.*`) in `AdditionalFiles` - This causes MSBuild to walk the entire directory tree during evaluation. The pattern `**\\*.*` is extremely broad and will match everything.\n\n2. **File I/O during evaluation** - `$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))` reads a file during project evaluation using a property function. \n\nThis synchronous I/O operation blocks evaluation and is particularly expensive.\n\n3. **Chained imports 3 levels deep** - `level1.props` → `level2.props` → `level3.props`. While three levels isn't severe, this nested import pattern can compound evaluation time and become problematic as it grows.","outputTokens":669},"id":"7520867f-470b-422b-860a-783c530dc3e9","timestamp":"2026-04-07T16:01:31.966Z","parentId":"b69da215-5b22-4eb7-9eec-f133f563c574"}
